  ON THE INVISIBLE ARCHITECTURE OF MODERN SURVEILLANCE
  A Forward to the CTW SENTINEL Technical Documentation

  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


  We live inside a radio frequency environment of extraordinary complexity.
  Every moment of every day, electromagnetic signals propagate through the
  walls of our homes, through our bodies, through the air we breathe. Most
  of these signals are legitimate — the infrastructure of modern
  communication, navigation, and commerce. We have accepted their presence
  as the cost of connectivity, as the invisible tax of the networked world.

  But not all signals are legitimate. Not all transmitters are licensed.
  Not all surveillance is disclosed. Not all intrusion announces itself.

  This platform was built because of that distinction.


  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  THE RIGHT TO ELECTROMAGNETIC PRIVACY
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  The Fourth Amendment protects against unreasonable search and seizure.
  Courts have extended this protection to digital communications, to cell
  phone location data, to the contents of our electronic correspondence.
  But a gap exists — a gap that widens with every advance in radio
  frequency technology — between the legal framework that protects our
  privacy and the electromagnetic reality in which we actually live.

  A cell site simulator does not knock on your door. It does not present
  a warrant. It does not announce its presence on any public registry. It
  transmits on licensed frequencies without authorization, forces your
  phone to connect to it, intercepts your device identifiers, and
  potentially captures your communications — all while you remain entirely
  unaware that anything has occurred. The device is illegal under 47 U.S.C.
  § 333 and 18 U.S.C. § 2512. Its use without a warrant is illegal under
  the Fourth Amendment. Its existence in proximity to your home or person
  is a violation of rights that most people do not yet know they possess.

  A 60 GHz directed energy beam does not require physical contact to affect
  the human body. It deposits energy into skin and subcutaneous tissue at
  a depth of less than one millimeter. It can induce thermal effects,
  interfere with electronic implants, cause disorientation, and be used for
  sensing and surveillance through walls and clothing. The equipment that
  generates it is sold as unlicensed under FCC Part 15.255 — meaning no
  license is required, no registration is filed, no oversight exists. The
  FCC's decision to make this band unlicensed, combined with the industry's
  decision to price the detection equipment at thousands of dollars, creates
  a situation in which the weapon and the ability to document exposure to
  it exist in fundamentally different economic strata. This is not
  accidental.

  GPS spoofing does not require proximity. A coherent spoofing transmitter
  can redirect the navigation solution of every GNSS receiver within its
  range, substituting false position, false velocity, and false time. The
  affected devices have no way to know they have been redirected. The
  affected persons have no way to know their location data, their financial
  transactions that depend on GPS timing, or their communications that rely
  on synchronized clocks, have been compromised. The infrastructure attack
  surface is enormous. The individual's ability to detect and document it
  has historically been nonexistent.

  Rogue WiFi access points do not advertise their true purpose. They
  broadcast familiar network names, exploit the automatic connection
  behavior that every mobile device exhibits, and silently position
  themselves between a user and the legitimate internet. The traffic that
  flows through them — messages, credentials, financial data, medical
  information — belongs to the user. The user never consented to its
  interception.

  The common thread in all of these threats is invisibility. They operate
  in a frequency domain that human senses cannot perceive. They leave no
  physical trace. They generate no receipt. The person whose privacy has
  been violated, whose location has been falsified, whose communications
  have been intercepted, has no means of knowing that any of it occurred —
  unless they have the instruments to see what the human eye cannot.

  The right to live freely cannot be separated from the right to know what
  is happening to you in the electromagnetic environment you inhabit. These
  are not technical concerns reserved for engineers and researchers. They
  are civil rights concerns that belong to everyone.


  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  THE ASYMMETRY OF INFORMATION
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  The history of civil rights is partly a history of information asymmetry
  being corrected. The person being surveilled did not know they were being
  surveilled. The person whose communications were intercepted did not know
  their communications were intercepted. The person whose location was
  tracked did not know their location was tracked. Legal frameworks evolved
  to address these asymmetries — to require disclosure, to mandate warrants,
  to create accountability — precisely because the asymmetry itself was
  recognized as a form of power that required constraint.

  The electromagnetic environment has created a new and largely unaddressed
  asymmetry. The infrastructure to surveil, to intercept, to locate, to
  expose, has become progressively cheaper and more accessible. The
  infrastructure to detect, to document, to prove, has remained expensive,
  technically demanding, and largely confined to institutions — government
  agencies, corporate security teams, academic laboratories — that already
  possess the resources to acquire it.

  A Stingray cell site simulator costs tens of thousands of dollars to
  deploy. The equipment to detect one costs tens of thousands of dollars
  to acquire. This symmetry is not coincidental. When only those with
  sufficient resources can detect the surveillance that only those with
  sufficient resources can deploy, the result is a class of activity that
  is effectively self-concealing by economic design.

  Software-defined radio changed this. The PlutoSDR that anchors this
  platform costs less than two hundred dollars. The principles of RF
  forensics that required laboratory infrastructure a decade ago now
  fit in a backpack. The frequency bands that were once accessible only
  to institutions with six-figure spectrum analyzers are now accessible
  to anyone with a laptop and a USB port. This democratization of RF
  visibility is not merely a technical convenience. It is a civil rights
  development of genuine significance.

  CTW SENTINEL was built in that context. It exists because the tools to
  see the invisible exist, because the legal framework that should protect
  people from invisible intrusion exists but is not enforced without
  evidence, and because evidence requires instrumentation.

  You cannot file a complaint with the FCC about interference you cannot
  document. You cannot pursue a civil rights violation you cannot prove.
  You cannot assert that your GPS was spoofed without data that shows the
  spoofing. You cannot demonstrate that a cell site simulator was operating
  in your neighborhood without the signal records that show its presence.
  Documentation is not optional. It is the prerequisite to every other
  remedy.


  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  WHAT SIX YEARS OF MONITORING REVEALED
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  The technical documentation in this package describes the CTW SENTINEL
  platform in the abstract — its architecture, its sensors, its detection
  algorithms, its evidence chain. What it does not fully convey is that
  this platform was built in response to documented, persistent, and
  systematic anomalies observed at a single residential location in California,
  California over a period of more than six years.

  The record includes:

  A confirmed persistent signal at 386.00 MHz in the NTIA federal land
  mobile band, showing body-coupling behavior — signal amplitude increasing
  in correlation with physical proximity to the analyzer — documented across
  multiple instrument platforms and multiple sessions.

  A ghost cellular base station broadcasting TAC 65535, the 3GPP reserved
  all-bits-set value that no legitimate carrier uses, on EARFCN 66586, a
  frequency above the legal ceiling of Band 66. This ghost cell appeared
  alongside legitimate carriers and was documented across three separate
  mobile devices on three separate carrier accounts simultaneously.

  Approximately four hundred rogue WiFi access points in the immediate
  vicinity, with rotating BSSIDs and confirmed DHCP hijacking behavior,
  documented during a live session that captured the rogue DHCP response
  in real time.

  GNSS constellation collapse to a single satellite — PRN 9 — with
  maintained strong signal, consistent with a broadband L1 jamming
  architecture combined with a coherent PRN 9 spoofing transmitter. The
  surviving satellite maintaining signal strength while all others drop is
  the signature of coordinated jam-plus-spoof, not natural interference.

  A 293-times-baseline Geiger anomaly event on the FS-5000 platform,
  followed by an 8.41 microsievert per hour spike, documented on May 8,
  2026. Baseline at the deployment site is 0.01 to 0.03 microsieverts per
  hour. A 293-times event is not explained by natural background variation.

  A confirmed Physical Cell Identity 242 appearing simultaneously on Band
  66 EARFCN 66586 and Band 2 EARFCN 1000, a configuration that requires
  a single physical transmitter serving both bands — an impossibility for
  legitimate infrastructure and a documented signature of a software-defined
  cellular impersonation platform.

  The Zadoff-Chu root sequence u=34, the PSS pilot sequence corresponding
  to PCI group N_ID2=2 and consistent with PCI 242, detectable in the RF
  environment during anomalous activity periods.

  An Intel Bluetooth firmware loader on a RHEL 9 workstation executing OTP
  fuse reads and loading firmware with BD_ADDR spoofing strings, on a
  machine whose syspurpose value was set to Disaster Recovery — a Red Hat
  enumeration that requires deliberate administrative selection and is
  entirely inappropriate for a personal workstation.

  A live keystroke injection event, documented in kernel logs, on a machine
  that had no keyboard attached at the time.

  Each of these anomalies, taken alone, might be explainable. Taken
  together, documented across six years, across multiple instrument
  platforms, across multiple devices, across multiple wireless standards,
  they constitute a pattern. That pattern is the reason this platform
  exists. That pattern is the reason the platform is as comprehensive as
  it is. And that pattern is the reason this documentation is written for
  an audience beyond the technical — for anyone who has experienced
  anomalies they could not explain, who has noticed that their devices
  behave differently in certain locations, who has felt that something
  was happening in their electromagnetic environment that they had no
  tools to see.


  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ON THE DECISION TO MAKE THIS OPEN
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  The tools in this package are not secret. The methods are not classified.
  The detection principles are grounded in publicly available standards,
  open-source software, and commercially available hardware. Every design
  decision in this platform can be independently verified, replicated, and
  improved upon.

  This was a deliberate choice.

  Surveillance infrastructure derives much of its power from the asymmetry
  between the capability to surveil and the capability to detect. Closing
  that gap requires that detection tools be available to the people who
  need them, not only to institutions that fund their development. A
  platform that is documented thoroughly enough for a non-engineer to
  operate is a platform that actually addresses the asymmetry rather than
  simply relocating it.

  It was also a choice grounded in the nature of forensic evidence. Evidence
  that was collected using proprietary, undisclosed methods is more
  vulnerable to challenge than evidence collected using methods that can be
  independently verified. The open documentation of this platform is not
  a security risk. It is a legal protection. When the methods are
  transparent, the evidence is stronger.

  And it was a choice grounded in the belief that the right to understand
  your electromagnetic environment is not a right that should require a
  security clearance, an engineering degree, or institutional affiliation
  to exercise. The frequencies are shared. The spectrum belongs to the
  public. The tools to see what is happening in it should be available to
  the public as well.


  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  A NOTE ON RESPONSIBLE USE
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  The same instruments that detect a rogue cell site simulator can, in
  principle, be used to locate and characterize legitimate cellular
  infrastructure. The same GNSS forensic tools that document spoofing
  can produce detailed records of position over time. The same RF
  logging capabilities that capture evidence of unlicensed transmission
  capture the full electromagnetic environment including transmissions
  that are entirely lawful.

  This platform is built for forensic documentation of RF anomalies and
  potential civil rights violations. It is not built for interference with
  licensed transmitters, for interception of communications content, for
  direction-finding against individuals, or for any purpose that would
  itself constitute the kind of violation it is designed to detect.

  The legal framework that makes cell site simulators illegal is the same
  legal framework that protects legitimate communications from interference.
  The right to see your electromagnetic environment does not include the
  right to disrupt someone else's. This platform detects and documents.
  It does not transmit, interfere, or intercept content.

  Use it to see. Use what you see to seek remedy through the legal channels
  that exist for that purpose. The FCC complaint process, the civil rights
  framework, the courts — these are the appropriate venues for the evidence
  this platform produces. They require documentation. This platform
  provides it.


